  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and has evolved significantly:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Originated from efforts to combat organized crime in the 1930s\n- Initial focus was on preventing criminal proceeds from being legitimized\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) - First major legislation requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- 1986 Money Laundering Control Act (US) - Established money laundering as a federal criminal offense\n- 1989 Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop international anti-money laundering standards\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed money laundering in drug trafficking\n- 1990 Council of Europe Convention expanded legal frameworks\n- Gradual global adoption of comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n4. Post-9/11 Expansion:\n- Patriot Act (2001) significantly expanded reporting requirements\n- Increased focus on combating terrorist financing\n- Enhanced international cooperation and information sharing\n\n5. Modern Era:\n- Continuous technological adaptation\n- Increased regulations around cryptocurrency\n- More sophisticated detection and prevention mechanisms\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with technological and financial innovations.",
